 Here we have $n=(3\cdot6\cdot10)(15\cdot21\cdot28)$. Taking the factors $3$, $5$, i.e., $5\geq3$ and $7$, $8$, $11$, we rewrite as below:
\begin{align*}
n&=2^3\cdot3^3\cdot5^2\cdot7^2\cdot3^1\cdot5^1\cdot7^1\cdot3^1\cdot5^1\cdot7^1(2^2\cdot3^2)\cdot7\cdot11\\
&=2^{3+2+2}\cdot3^{3+1+1+2}\cdot5^{2+1+1}\cdot7^{2+1+1+1+1}\cdot11\\
&=2^7\cdot3^7\cdot5^4\cdot7^6\cdot11\text{.}
\end{align*} <answer>Right. Now note that the term $7$ is non-zero. Hence, the following equality holds:
\begin{fact*}
Let $n=x_1^{a_1}x_2^{a_2}\cdots x_k^{a_k}$, where $x_i$ are distinct prime factors and $a_i$ are positive integers.
\[ \sqrt{n}=\sqrt{x_1^{a_1}x_2^{a_2}\cdots x_k^{a_k}} = x_1^{\frac{a_1}{2}}x_2^{\frac{a_2}{2}}\cdots x_k^{\frac{a_k}{2}} \iff \{a_i\} \text{ is even, for all } 1\leq i \leq k. \] In addition, if $\{a_i\}$ is odd, then:
\begin{align*}
& \left\{ \begin{aligned}
x_i^{\frac{a_i}{2}} &=\sqrt{x_{i}x_i} \text{, which is a prime number, for all }1 \leq k\leq m\\
x_{k+1}^{\frac{a_{k+1}}{2}} &=x_{k+1}\cdot\sqrt{x_{k+1}} \text{, which is a perfect square, for all } m+1\leq k\leq n\text{.} \\
\end{aligned} \right.\\
& \text{ Hence, } \sqrt{n}=\begin{cases}
\text{a perfect square, if } m\geq 2,\\
x_{k+1}\cdot\sqrt{x_{k+1}} \text{, for all } k\in \mathbb{N}; \text{ that is,}\\
x+x^2\text{, for all } x\in \mathbb{N};\\
\end{cases}\end{align*} If we take $m=7$, then $\sqrt{n}$ is the solution. <qed> </answer>

